{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600532/1930112301/0024.xml":{"full_text":"FUN TASKS BANISH\nCHILDREN\u2019S PAIN\nHospital Recreation Super\nvisor Tells How Problems\nAre Mastered.\nTony was sick and fretful and, worse\nthan all. just bored to death as any\nnormal boy of 8 would be after weeks\nin a hospital bed.\nt Tony's mental state actually had be\ncome contagious among the erstwhile\ncheerful little patients in this particular\nward of Children's Hospital when Mrs.\nMary R. Weller, the recreation super\nvisor. entered one day and sensed the\nsituation with a single experienced\nglance.\n\u201cNow what's the mater. Tony?\u201d she\nasked as she patted his rebellious curly\nhead.\n\u201cAw. I'm just sick and tired of lying\nhere all day, I want something to play\nwith,\u201d Tony rebelled.\nMrs Weller, who had her own ides,\nfetched him a monkey on a string and\na mechanical toy.\nFor about 30 minutes Tony appeared\nperfectly satisfied and contented. He\nmade the monkey jump and laughed at\nits antics and he ran the little engine i\nup and down a board. For a while his\ntroubles were ended.\nBut wise Mrs. Weller, who knows the\nways of children far better than most\nof us. knew otherwise. She waited pa\ntiently until Tony tired of his play\nthings and threw them aside to renew\nhis fretfulness.\nMrs. Weller went to the play room\nand returned with a piece of card board\nand a pair of scissors.\nNew Interest Aroused.\n\"Now let's make some animals.\u201d she\ntold Tony and with experienced skill\nshe cut out a ferocious looking tiger.\nTony cocked his head to one side and\nc registered interest.\n\u201cSuppose you see what you can do.\u201d\nMrs. Weller suggested, turning over the\nimplements.\n\u201cTony cut out a dog. At least he\nsaid it was a dog. He next tried some\nthing else. It soon absorbed his inter\nim. est and he was the envy of all the other\nT children in the ward.\nFinally one little girl couldn't con\nceal her wish any longer. \"Let me try\nIt,\u201d she pleaded.\n\u201cMe too.\u201d arose the ward chorus.\nThat was how a piece of paper and a\npair of scissors started a game in this\nward of sick children that lasted a\nweek. Mrs. Weller supervised it and\neach child tried to cut out some differ\nent figure. \"Before the week was over\nI counted 60 different objects these\nboys and girls had cut out themselves,\u201d\nshe said. \u2018They thought them all out\non their own Initiative. That ward was\na happy and contended place all week.\u201d\nMrs. Weller told this story merely to\nIllustrate the kind of recreational work\nthat is being done at Children\u2019s Hos\npital Mental or occupational therapy,\nyou may call it. but whatever it is. the\nattending physicians are enthusiastic\nabout the value of it.\nMrs. Weller explained it was simply\nteaching children that they have this\npower to do creative, inventive work\nand that expensive toys are unnecessary\nwhen they can indulge their own facili\nties for self entertainment. 6he be\nlieves that is one of the most important\nI things\u2014perhaps the most important\nthing\u2014to develop in a child.\nHas Way With Children.\nFor six years Mrs. Weller has been\ndoing just that thing at Children\u2019s Hos-\nI pltal She has away with children.\nWhenever there is a particularly prob\nlemmatical case, it\u2019s the habit with the\nnurses to say, \"Go get Mrs. Weller,\nshe'll quiet him down.\u201d And she does,\nwithout fail, by getting the child\u2019s mind\noff his pain or sickness and interested\nin entertaining himself in away that\nhas source without end.\nIf parents could only understand the\nuses to whieh odds and ends in their\nhousehold could be put to entertaining\ntheir children, she contends, their\npocketbooks as well as their patience\nwould not be so sorely 1 axed.\nA hospital is an ideal place to pick\nup scraps of amusement for children\nwhose minds simply must be taken from\ntheir own troubles if they are to get\nwell and strong again.\n1 Every one knows about the little sticks\nwith which the nurses, after applying\ncotton on the ends, swab out the pa\ntient\u2019s throat. These are ideal for\nmany other purposes, and Mrs. Waller\nteaches her boys and girls how to weave\nthem into tiny baskets or into small\nchairs, some of which are offered for\nsale in the Thrift Shop at Tenth and\nE streets, where Mrs. Weller wljl ex\nhibit some of the work this week.\nBut it is not with the idea of selling\ntheir articles that Mrs. Weller spends\nhours in instructing the children. \"It\u2019s\nfor their own self-expression, to create\nresourcefulness in entertainment,\u201d she\nstresses.\nOne of the most popular things in the\nplayroom is a small loom. Mrs. Weller\ndidn't know how to operate it when it\narrived, so she experimented with it\nand made the children do likewise.\nThey solved the \u201ccombination\u201d eventu\nally and now happy hours are'spent by\nconvalescents weaving mats and small\nrugs.\nBoy Prise Lace Maker.\nA 7-year-old boy is the prize lace\nmaker at the hospital Just now. It isn't\nnecessary to buy expensive material to\nmake lace A hospital has no end of\nmosquito netting and when it is un\nraveled, the threads can be made into\nall sorts of attractive lace articles. Un\nder the skillful fingers of eager children,\ncrepe napkins and towels are being\nf Thompson Bros. V\nW evjcu THE RIVER /TO LOWER I'RIIW\no/Hflje&Uc\nBY owr Home Is Not\nComplete Without a\nModel 52, Complete\nModel 131, Complete\nI;- THOMPSON BROTHERS\nFurniture, Stoves, Floor Coverings\nPhonographs, Radios\nf 1220 Good Hope Rd., Anacostia, D. C., Line. 0556\nI\n\u201cMOTHER\u201d TO ALL THE SICK AT CHILDREN\u2019S HOSPITAL\njr* \u2019Na. 'V\nWhen there is a fretful child at Children's Hospital Mrs. Mary R. Weller is called in for eonsultation. She never\nvet has failed in a situation. In the above photo Mrs. W eller is comforting Elmer Stone, left, and Guy Ewell right.\n\u2014Star Staff Photo.\nI\nI transformed into fruits and flowers, as\nis also paper maehe, which is excellent\nmaterial for vases and jars.\nWhen Mrs. Ridley McLean endowed\nthis important hospital work, she gen\nerously told Mrs. Weller to spend as\nmuch as she liked for toys or anything\nelse to entertain the little patients.\n\u201cNo. the children would have too\nmuch then, it would kill their creative\ninstinct,\u201d Mrs. Weller reasoned. That\nis her method and it has worked won\nders, as all the doctors and therapists\nagree.\nMrs. Weller likes to tell about a small\ncolored girl who left the hospital after\nmonths of illness. She was offered any\ntoy she wished to take home. What\nshe chose, instead of a prettlty dressed\ndoll, was one of the pictures some of\nthe children had made.\nMost of the children are so young,\nshe explained, yet they respond so\nquickly to creative suggestions that her j\nwork holds unfailing interest. Many\nof the mothers have seized upon the\nidea and carry it on in their homes.\n\"That Is the most encouraging feature\nof it all,\u201d she said.\nLIEUT. VAUPRE WINS\nMITCHELL TROPHY\nAverages 146.7 Miles Per Hour\nOver 120-Mile Course in\nSpeed Event.\nBy the Associated Press.\nSELFRIDGE FIELD. MOUNT CLEM\nENS, Mich., November 22.\u2014Lieut. Louis\nA. Vaupre, attached to the 36th Pur\nsuit Squadron, captured the Mitchell\nTrophy, a major military flying award,\nin the annual speed event here today.\nLieut. Vaupre\u2019s elapsed time was 49\nminutes. 39.75 seconds, an average of\n146.7 miles per hour over the 120-mile\ntriangular course.\nFlying a Curtis P-1, standard army\npursuit plane, Lieut. Vaupre nosed out\nLieut. George F. Smith of the 37th\nSquadron, whose time was 49:51:76, of\n145.96 miles an hour. Third was Lieut.\nTheodore M. Bolen of the 27th, with\n49:52:38 elapsed time, averaging 145.93\nmiles per hour.\nTwo groups of army planes partici\npated in the event, the Curtiss P-l\u2019s\nand the Curtiss P-6\u2019s, the latter newer\nand faster Army ships, which carried\na six-minute handicap.\nAll of the ships finishing in first four\nplaces were P-l\u2019s, the handicap prov\ning too heavy for the faster ships to\novercome.\nThe speed event was marked by three\naccidents. Lieut. Frank J. Coleman of\nthe 17th Pursuit Squadron, made a\nforced landing on a highway and drove\nhis plane into a tree, smashing a wing.\nHe was uninjured. Lieut. Emmett\nFyoet, of the 27th Squadron, made a\nforced landing in a bank at the end of\nthe field, but his plane was not\ndamaged. Lieut. Bryant L. Boatner of\nthe 27th Squadron, taxied his plane\ninto a pylon at the close of the race,\ndamaging the ship s propeller.\nMURDER TRIAL DELAYED\nMother. Accused of Killing Daugh\nter, Found 111.\nDENVER. November 22 (fP). \u2014Illness\nagain prevented Mrs. Pearl O\u2019Loughlin,\naccused of slaying her 10-year-old\nstepdaughter. Leona, from appearing in\nDistrict Court today to have a formal\norder issued delaying opening of her\ntrial from Monday to next Friday.\nJudge Henry A. Calvert stated yes\ni terday the trial would be postponed\ni until Friday because of her illness, re\nsuiting from a spinal puncture made\ni to determine whether she is afflicted\nwith a mental or nervous disorder.\nTHE SUNDAY STAR, WASHINGTON. D. C.. NOVEMBER 33, 1930-PART ONE.\nPLAN TO IDENTIFY DISEASES\nBY NUMBERS IS CONSIDERED\nNational Medical Conference to Discuss\nApplication of System Analogous\nto Foot Ball Signals.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. November 22.\u2014A pro- i\nposal to adopt in medicine the foot bell\nsignal system which calls plays by code\nnumbers will be considered by national j\nmedical authorities here Monday.\nThe medical numbers will identify i\nthe 20.000 distinct diseases and lesions\nagainst which American physicians are\nbattling.\nThe purpose is to identify more ef\nfectively for all doctors the large class\nof diseases wnich have obscure but im\nportant complcations likely to be over-\nFoot Ball Analogy Applied.\nIt is like regarding disease and the\ndoctors as two opposing elevens, with\nthe ball in possession of disease. The\ncode gives the defending medical men\na means of Identifying the oncoming\n\u201chidden ball\u201d tactics of the disease\nattack.\nIt has been drawn up in printed form\nfor consideration of the National Con\nference on Nomenclature of Disease\nmeeting at the New York Academy of\nMedicine. This Is the first meeting of\nthe kind in this country. The Public\nHealth Relations Committee of the\nacademy sponsored the Idea two years\nago.\nThe report says the present 20.000\nnames do not always Indicate the nature\nof diseases specifically enough. The re\nsult 1$ that statistics do not always tru\nLONDON BANKERS\nSEE RECOVERY AHEAD\nSurplus Stocks Are Declared Last\nObstacle to Return of\nProsperity.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. November 32.\u2014Henry i\nSchroder Co., prominent London\nbanking firm, says in its quarterly re\nview today that American manufac\nturers and merchants apparently have\narrived at the conclusion that surplus\nstocks are the last, but all-important\nobstacle to sound business recovery.\n\u201cThe current reductions being made\nin retail prices, and plans to reduce\nprices still further, are well conceived,\u201d\nsays the review, \"and may be expected\nto Increase consumption, reduce stocks\nin terms of sales, and start the whole 1\ncycle of industrial recovery In motion.\u201d!\nInstall Later\nThe Famous American Radiator Co.\nFirst Quality Product Installed\nThis low prico includas\ncomploto unit for 6-room\nhouse. 18-in. boiler, 6\nradiators, 300 ft. radia- 9\ntion, fully installed for L\nat low at V\nif HM No Cash\njf Down Payment\n5 Years to p \u00aey\nMKfIHMI Nothing down until plant has\nHflyfifi\u00dfll\u00df been installed. Then pay the\nbill monthly over 3 years.\nBuy Money!\nHere\u2019s a modern hot-water plant, made and guar\nteed by the American Radiator Co., that will give\nyou years of heating satisfaction. Buy now at the\npresent low price. We\u2019ll install immediately with\nx little interruption to your home.\nGENERAL HEATING CO\nHeating and numbing Contractors\n901 lOmSt.N.W. Nat\u2019l3o66-7\nly represent the experience of physi\ncians. and the country's \"health book\nkeeping\u201d is incomplete.\nCause and Location Indicated.\nThe numbers purpose to classify dis\nease first according to the part of the\nbody it affects, and second by its cause.\nWhen the cause is unknown, the num\nbers identify \"the tracks which the\ncause leaves.\u201d\nIn the foot ball analogy, the gridiron\nfor this game is the human body, and\ninstead of yard lines the physicians are\nmarking it off with a system of latitude\nand longitude in disease, which is as\ndefinite under their practices as tha dif\nference between a two-yard and a 20-\nyard gain on the field.\nConfusion in Meaning Prevented.\nThus if the code is adopted a physi\ncian may report that a patient has\n612-14. That means \u201ca protozoan in\nfection of the tongue.\u201d When a physi\ncian in San Francisco reads that alae\nwhere doctors are treating 613-14, the\nWesterner knows exactly what Is meant:\nbut with present names he might not\nknow.\nThe committee making Monday\u2019s re\nport includes representatives of the\nAmerican Medical Association, Amer\nican Public Health Association, Amer\nican Statistical Association, American\nHospital Association and various Fed\neral medical and statistical servloea.\nAUTO KILLS 4-YEAR-OLD\nHagerstown Girl Run Down in\nAttempt to Cross Street.\nSpecial Dispatch to Tht Star.\nHAGERSTOWN. Md., November 23\nLouise Bragg. 4 years old. daughtar of\nMr and Mrs. Jacob Bragg, was killed\ntonight near her home when she ran\ninto the street just as the car driven\nby Herbert Daughty. colored, backed\ninto the curb. Daughty was released,\nthe accident being found unavoidable.\nTelephone National\n5000\nFor Immediate delivery of The\nStar to your borne every evening\nand Bunday morning. The\nRoute Agent will collect at the\nend of each month, at the rate\nof cents per day and 6 cents\nSunday.\nEINSTEIN DREADS\nNEW YORK CROWD\nFear of Reception Clouds\nScientist\u2019s Pleasure at\nAmerican Trip.\nBy the Associated Press.\nBERLIN, November 22. \u2014What Prof.\nAlbert Einstein fears most about his\napproaching visit to the Urilted States\nis his arrival in New York, he told the\nAssociated Press today.\nWith an expression of pain and be\nwilderment on his face, he said the\ndread of having a fuss made over him\nhad cast a shadow over his entire\njourney. This was planned as a quiet\nand private pleasure trip to New York.\nCuba and the Panama Canal, followed\nby a period of concentrated study and\nan Interchange of Ideas and Informa\ntion with American savants at Pasa\ndena. Calif.\nOrdeal la Breaded.\n\"Facing the cameramen and aubmit\nting to the cross-fire of the newspaper\nmen's questions are enough of an ordeal,\nbut that will be over in a few min\nutes,\" said the father of the relativity\ntheory.\n\"Then the real difflcultiM will begin.\nIt\u2019s the crowds, the Invitations, the\nspeeches that I abhor. For that reason\nI am thinking seriously of remaining\naboard the Belgenland until we leave\nfor Cuba.\u201d\nWith a puzzled air he revealed that\ntens of thousands of dollars had been\noffered him by American firms deal\ning in disinfectants, toilet waters,\nhaberdashery, musical Instruments,\nclothing and what not, if he would\noonaent to sign hia name to statements\nthat he had used the articles and found\nthem satisfactory.\nAmazed at Corruption.\n\"Is it not a sad commentary upon\nthe commercialism and. I must add. the\ncorruption of our time that business\nfirms make these offers with no thought\nof wanting to insult me?\u201d he asked,\nwith a shake of his head. \u201cIt evidently\nmeans that this form of corruption\u2014\nfor corruption it is\u2014is a widespread\none.\u201d\nProf. Einstein explained that his\nwhole purpose in going to America was\na scientific one.\n\"Pasadena and Mount Wilson Ob\nservatory have the most perfect equip\nment In the world of the kind I use\nmuon mi\u2014in i in\n\nGift Economies\njTpos'A Make Your Selections Now and Save! Scores of\nA r .*S. y Practical Suggestions\u2014at Unbelievably LOW PRICES!\nRegular $8.50 \u201cGUNN* Regular $25\nTelephone Stand Sectional Bookcase ar\nholatered chair ut 13 by 16. Covered i/\\\nKyfr v jag, Mat l\u2014nllK\"\"'\" 5 ainaii wnaenin mohair or velour\nS3O English /fflTirniX Regular $37.50 Regular $35 _\nClub Chair\nCoil Bod Springs *6** *\u2018J\nn a -.11 HC3&\u00ab3\u00bb' \u00a9ate-Leg Table\nI based. He \u2018\u201cl l t ed In $/T QQ Size 35 by 48\nall standard sizes. j n mahogany fin s||.so\nOur Enlarged Rug Department\nIs Complete With Products of the Nation\u2019s Foremost Makers!\nNATIONALLY FAMOUS MELLISTAN- 9x12 WORSTED WILTON RUGS. Finest\nANGLO ORIENTAL and AMERICAN nI I C qualities. Kamak, Barrymore and Wash-\nORIENTAL RUGS. 9x12 size. They have RUSS TOr every \"ngton wide selection^and excentSnll\nthe same silky sheen as real Persian Rugs, lon wiae seieouon and exceptional\nfrom which they are copied. The lowest j\u00bb+ avoru values.\nprices ever quoted on these rugs were iv/L/fii ai cveiy dT/- e dtl^C\n$157.50 and $lB5. c sOj tO 3>IZO\nSurely yeu II find the type of rug\nS9B and SI 25 p* floorcov rina vou went in our\nw extensive assortment*. Plein broad\nloom carpeta in every color end 9x12 WILTON VELVET RUGS, the noted\nFINE 9x12 AXMINSTER RUGS. Such width, stair end hall earpets Felt- Irvington and Meadowbrook makes. Beau-\nSel\u201d a potomac Us Ca\u2018 thn e \u00b0an V d A?S!e5: h' U qu ality nd shades *nd pattwn. to\nEvery desirable shade. widths end grades. Oval Chemiie harmonize with every room scheme.\nJ Ruga\u2014Hook Rugs\u2014Rugs for the\n$27.50 to $55 \u00ab.th H,.m la varieu, ,v.liti,a $55\nLow Terms 7/lAf Convenient\nArranged wm MT I P a I I\n905-907 7th St. N.w. rayments\nLIZARDS, CRICKETS, GRASSHOPPERS\nCOME OUT IN SPRINGLIKE WEATHER\nTrees and Flowers Declared Budding Near Cumberland.\nHunterford Wild Plants Growing in Woods.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nCUMBERLAND. Md., November 22.\n\u2014The absence of black or killing frosts,\ncoupled with misty rains, fog and sun\nshine In recent days, has caused Spring\nlike conditions in this territory. Vege\ntation Is awake, the ground lizards have\ncome out to see the sun. the crickets\nhave left their hiding places and the\ngrasshoppers are shedding their Fall\ncoats for a vernal ensemble. All over\nCumberland gardeners and floral lovers\nare seeing peculiar conditions. The\ncrocus is peeping through lawns, maple\nIn my work,\" he said. \u2018\u2018Not that I ex\npect to undertake experiments In Cali\nfornia which I could not make her*.\nAs far as that goes, I can just as well\ndo my work In my little study In the\ngarret.\n\"But I do want to exchange Infor\nmation and compare notes with the\nAmerican scientists in Pasadena.\"\nu. d. cTsesslotTends\nWITH INSTALLATION\nMrs. Charles B. Faris of St. Louis,\nSecond Vice President\nGeneral.\nBy the Associated Press.\nASHEVILLE, N. C.. November 22.\nWith the installation of newly elected\ngeneral officers tonight, the annual con\nvention of the United Daughters of the\nConfederacy came to a close. The of- 1\nfleers installed were: Mrs. Charles B\nFaris of St. Louis, second vice president\ngeneral: Mrs. George Dismukes, Chicka\nsha. Okla.. treasurer-general, and Miss\nAlice Baxter, Atlanta, Ga., honorary\npresident general.\nMrs. L. M. Bashinsky of Troy. Ala.,\npresident general, and other officers\nwere not up for re-election, having been\nelected last year for two-year terms.\nThe next convention will be held in\nJacksonville. Fla The Daughters at\nthis convention voted unanimously to\nassume responsibility for paying the\nfinal $50,000 of the purchase price for\nStratford Hall, in Virginia, birthplace\nof Gen. Robert E. Lee.\ntrees have well developed bud* and the\nlilac and shrub threaten to bloom\nagain.\nThe fine, misty rain* and fogs have\nbrought back all the lawns to a green\ncolor that has not existed since early\nSummer.\nIn the woods, the hunters say, the\nviolet, the teaberry, the trailing arbutus\nand the wild honeysuckle appear to be\nIn doubt whether to bud and bloom.\nThe huckleberry seems to be showing\nsigns of extending Its tendrills and\ngrowing another crop. Not for years\nhas such a condition existed.\nLABOR DECLARED RELIEF\nNEEDED BY U. S. FARMER\nNewly Elected Union President\nUrges $3,000,000,000 Non-In\nterest Loan for Improvement.\nBy the Associated Press.\nST. PAUL, November 23 Labor, not\nfarm relief, is the greatest need of the\ncountry In the belief of John A. Simp\nson, Bethany, Okla., newly elected pres\nident of the National Parmers\u2019 Union,\nwhich closed its convention here yes\nterday.\n\u201cWhen people are working they will\nbuy flour and cotton and automobiles,\u201d\nhe said. \u201cMore relief to the fanner is\ngoing to put him farther In the hole.\u201d\nSimpson advocated a plan whereby\nthe Federal Government would print\n$3,000,000,000 in non-interest currency,\nto be loaned to the States or spent by\nthe Government on improvement proj\nects all over the country to relieve un-\nI employment.\nMORROW SPENT $18,765\nSenator-Elect Files Statement of\nCampaign Expense.\nTRENTON, N. J.. November 22 OP).\u2014\nA final statement by Dwight W. Morrow\nto the secretary of State today showed\n$18,765.02 was spent in his campaign\nfor election to the United States Senate.\nThe Republican Senator-elect re\nceived contributions of $24,569.50. His\nwife gave $2,599 and Mr. Morrow him\nself contributed $5,000.\nB-7\n$3,000 NEEDED IN PAGE\nFOR DROUGHT RELIEF\nCounty Committee Drafting Every\nAble Citizen to Aid Those\nin Want.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nLURAY, Va, November 32.\u2014The Page\nCounty Drought Relief Committee is\ndrafting every able citizen In an effort\nto relieve the needy people in the\ncounty.\nOn an estimate based on a census\njust made it will take at least $3,000\nper month to provide these people with\neven the barest requirements to sustain\nlife. Two hundred dollars of this fund\nhas been provided by the board of\nsupervisors. A part is expected to come\nfrom the Red Cross and individuals and\norganizations will be asked for the rest.\n\nBIBLE READ 19 TIMES\nBY BETHEL. VA., MAN\nBy the Associated Press.\nBETHEL. Va.. November 22.\u2014J. J.\nWall, 81. is credited with reading the\nBible through 19 times sinoe 1920.\nHe says he has kept a record of the\nstarting and finishing dates of each\nreading.\nE-Natural\nPlates\nOs exceptional beauty and\nappearance. A plate that as\nsures comfort as wall aa re\nstoring original facial featuras.\nSee Thit Crmotion mnj\nComparo It With Otkmrm\nOUR LOW PRICES\nplace hlth-rradt dentistry within\nI reach et ererr cne. Coma ia far aa\nexamination. It's free.\nHandmade plateo. $lO. sls. CM-\nOther plateo In cold, alamtaum. sil\nver and all porcelain. MMs In at\ntendant*.\nDR. FREIOT\n407 7th ST. N.W.\n\u25a0oar* A.M. to d P.M\nInndaro. 1$ A.M. to 1 T.M.\nPhone National 0019","height":"25350","width":"19671"}}
